INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmhr0jpnt00032gxijpyya93j','[{"title":"Automatic Recaptures Without Calculating Consequences","description":"The player repeatedly makes automatic recaptures without assessing the resulting position. In mistakes #1, #9, #14, and #28, they explicitly mention \"automatic recapture\" or capturing back without proper evaluation. As they note in mistake #1: \"Captured back without assessing Qxg3\" and in mistake #28: \"I just made an automatic recapture on d4, but Qf6 is a pretty simple double attack.\"","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Systematic Blindness to ''Sneaky Pins''","description":"The player has a recurring blind spot for pin tactics, particularly involving queen-versus-rook alignments. In mistakes #13, #19, and #35, they explicitly identify missing \"sneaky pin\" tactics. As they reflect in mistake #19: \"maybe a little psychological since the rook is opposite the queen which usually plays to the rook''s advantage, but not if it is unprotected.\"","mistakeCount":3},{"title":"Tunnel Vision and Avoiding Simple Calculations","description":"The player frequently gets fixated on one idea and fails to consider simple, obvious alternatives. In mistakes #2, #3, #27, #29, and #39, they describe tunnel vision or not considering straightforward moves. They note in mistake #3: \"I just played by vague feel\" and in mistake #39: \"I need to focus on simple, short calculations, and avoid fancy play syndrome.\"","mistakeCount":5},{"title":"Psychological Aversion to Trading Queens and Bishops","description":"The player has an admitted psychological resistance to making certain exchanges, particularly queen trades and bishop-for-knight exchanges. In mistakes #5, #11, #25, and #33, they identify avoiding beneficial trades. They explicitly state in mistake #5: \"I have a blindness for both exchanging queens and for exchanging bishop for knight\" and in mistake #11 mention trading \"a bishop for a knight like this as a blind spot.\"","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Fancy Play Syndrome and Impulsive Overcomplication","description":"The player repeatedly rejects simple, strong moves in favor of complicated or extreme ideas, even against their better judgment. In mistakes #8, #10, #32, #37, and #39, they identify \"fancy play syndrome\" or impulsive decisions. As they admit in mistake #37: \"I saw that this move lost a pawn but played it anyway figuring I''d have some vague compensation. In reality there is nothing. I need to be more disciplined with my move process.\"","mistakeCount":5}]',43,1762650416297,'["cmhr0h1j300022gxi4zyogg2e","cmhqqszkc000f2gac8rumvhqt","cmhqqrxqo000d2gacnduiytyz","cmhqqr30y000b2gac57qzwa6b","cmhqpupdb00082gac2e9ekfp4","cmhqpau4c00052gaclu22i8hp","cmhqouy1c00022gacytoj2tbo","cmhqoeg0x00022g6kk76prlmz","cmhqm3hv900042ggzc056ax1s","cmhoar9ez00022g3ggzs1gr2b","cmhnvo229001m2ghesmyody1d","cmhnvl5ri001j2ghe48oqludj","cmhnvghg7001g2ghesi4ueewr","cmhnverm6001d2ghe5ski16eo","cmhnv9qsg001a2gheytde3n4d","cmhnv6jhz00172ghenzl80y36","cmhnv3rv300142ghe3vfyhh3i","cmhnv1k5g00112ghenz5j0ciw","cmhnv068n000y2ghel8qusd19","cmhnuv0ru000v2gheu1xibaqa","cmhnuou9q000s2ghe8ohfea18","cmhnulz55000p2ghe6mqsjftt","cmhnuk2up000m2ghe69dqz959","cmhnue655000j2ghed931hyfj","cmhnuaxuy000g2gheqb6lb0f7","cmhnu84yj000d2gheojxnf43y","cmhnu5wvm000a2ghe21rokhpz","cmhnu34ho00072ghe2i12xojn","cmhnu1uxe00052ghekihzscis","cmhntztdw00022gheeldf1xwq","cmhnrc34a00052g016f2b5fhx","cmhnqmbxf00022g01x6bubskj","cmhmnpwkg000l2gv7lclohiec","cmhmnoa2z000j2gv78mty3n4h","cmhmnlwk5000g2gv7cqcsvzxa","cmhmnkl2t000e2gv7retl0usl","cmhmnhttz000b2gv72vsqpx63","cmhmneqx000072gv7sq5sq7n7","cmhmnbw2w00032gv7v9enfpk0","cmhmmf2f100082gid5936azhw","cmhmkvgvl00062gidmnzrgvse","cmhmkst5300032gid5tjk6kqh","cmhmadt4w00032gx9beexbw2w"]');
INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmhtkek8300032gge7vctjezt','[{"title":"Blind Spot: Avoiding Bishop-for-Knight Exchanges","description":"The player explicitly recognizes a recurring blindness to trading bishops for knights, calling it a \"blind spot\" multiple times. In mistakes #2, #7, #13, they note this bias: \"I have a bias toward worrying too much about bishop-for-knight exchanges\" and \"I often miss trading a bishop for a knight like this as a blind spot.\" This psychological aversion causes them to miss strong tactical opportunities.","mistakeCount":3},{"title":"Fancy Play Syndrome and Overcomplication","description":"The player repeatedly chooses complex, fancy moves over simple, effective ones. In mistakes #1, #10, #12, #34, #41, they explicitly identify \"fancy play syndrome\" and note: \"Could have just played the simple Ng4\" and \"I need to focus on simple, short calculations, and avoid fancy play syndrome.\" This pattern includes panicking into extreme moves and seeking compensation without concrete justification.","mistakeCount":5},{"title":"Automatic Recaptures Without Assessment","description":"The player makes automatic recaptures without calculating consequences, particularly in tactical positions. In mistakes #3, #11, #16, #30, they note: \"Automatic recapture\" and \"I just made an automatic recapture on d4\" without checking for opponent''s threats. This automation leads to missing double attacks, pins, and better alternatives.","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Tunnel Vision and Calculation Blindness","description":"The player shows a pattern of not even considering certain moves or calculating basic sequences. In mistakes #4, #5, #6, #9, #14, #29, #31, they repeatedly write \"didn''t even notice,\" \"didn''t even consider,\" and \"somehow I just thought\" without actually calculating. This includes missing obvious moves like a mate in one (mistake #9) due to narrow focus.","mistakeCount":7},{"title":"Psychological Avoidance of Queen Exchanges","description":"The player has an irrational tendency to avoid queen trades even when beneficial. In mistakes #7, #27, #35, #45, they explicitly acknowledge avoiding queen exchanges \"for no reason\" and note this psychological bias costs them: \"I also psychologically was probably avoiding the queen exchange for no reason\" and being \"too focused on avoiding a queen trade.\" This pairs with their bishop-for-knight bias as a broader exchange-avoidance issue.","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Missing ''Sneaky Pins'' with Queen-Rook Alignments","description":"The player has a specific tactical blind spot for pins involving queens opposite rooks. In mistakes #15, #21, #37, they explicitly call these \"sneaky pin\" situations and note: \"maybe a little psychological since the rook is opposite the queen which usually plays to the rook''s advantage, but not if it is unprotected.\" This represents a concrete tactical pattern they fail to recognize.","mistakeCount":3}]',45,1762804700644,'["cmhtkcu0900022ggek89uta5c","cmhsi7iwc00022glb5gxjeiov","cmhr0h1j300022gxi4zyogg2e","cmhqqszkc000f2gac8rumvhqt","cmhqqrxqo000d2gacnduiytyz","cmhqqr30y000b2gac57qzwa6b","cmhqpupdb00082gac2e9ekfp4","cmhqpau4c00052gaclu22i8hp","cmhqouy1c00022gacytoj2tbo","cmhqoeg0x00022g6kk76prlmz","cmhqm3hv900042ggzc056ax1s","cmhoar9ez00022g3ggzs1gr2b","cmhnvo229001m2ghesmyody1d","cmhnvl5ri001j2ghe48oqludj","cmhnvghg7001g2ghesi4ueewr","cmhnverm6001d2ghe5ski16eo","cmhnv9qsg001a2gheytde3n4d","cmhnv6jhz00172ghenzl80y36","cmhnv3rv300142ghe3vfyhh3i","cmhnv1k5g00112ghenz5j0ciw","cmhnv068n000y2ghel8qusd19","cmhnuv0ru000v2gheu1xibaqa","cmhnuou9q000s2ghe8ohfea18","cmhnulz55000p2ghe6mqsjftt","cmhnuk2up000m2ghe69dqz959","cmhnue655000j2ghed931hyfj","cmhnuaxuy000g2gheqb6lb0f7","cmhnu84yj000d2gheojxnf43y","cmhnu5wvm000a2ghe21rokhpz","cmhnu34ho00072ghe2i12xojn","cmhnu1uxe00052ghekihzscis","cmhntztdw00022gheeldf1xwq","cmhnrc34a00052g016f2b5fhx","cmhnqmbxf00022g01x6bubskj","cmhmnpwkg000l2gv7lclohiec","cmhmnoa2z000j2gv78mty3n4h","cmhmnlwk