INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmhtpo1t7000gs0tmj1v47z7r','[{"title":"Blind Spot: Trading Bishop for Knight","description":"The player repeatedly acknowledges a systematic blindness to beneficial bishop-for-knight trades, calling it a \"bias\" and \"blind spot.\" In mistakes #8, #13, and #19, they explicitly note missing tactical opportunities because they avoid considering these exchanges, with mistake #8 stating \"I have a bias toward worrying too much about bishop-for-knight exchanges\" and mistake #19 noting \"it requires me to consider Bxf3 which is ''antipositional'' and I often miss trading a bishop for a knight like this as a blind spot.\"","mistakeCount":3},{"title":"Automatic Moves Without Calculating Opponent''s Threats","description":"The player frequently makes \"automatic\" recaptures or natural-looking moves without checking for opponent''s tactical resources. In mistakes #9, #17, #22, #25, #36, and #43, they describe playing moves reflexively, with mistake #36 noting \"I just made an automatic recapture on d4, but Qf6 is a pretty simple double attack\" and mistake #25 warning they \"should have seen that Rd7 Nfe5 would be a tactical issue\" before playing the \"natural\" move blindly.","mistakeCount":6},{"title":"Recurring Blindness to ''Sneaky Pins'' with Queen","description":"The player has a specific tactical blind spot for pins involving the queen opposite a rook or unprotected piece. In mistakes #21, #27, and #43, they identify missing pins, with mistake #21 stating \"Again it was a queen opposite a rook sneaky pin that I overlooked\" and mistake #27 noting \"maybe a little psychological since the rook is opposite the queen which usually plays to the rook''s advantage, but not if it is unprotected.\"","mistakeCount":3},{"title":"Fancy Play Syndrome Instead of Simple Moves","description":"The player consistently chooses complicated or \"fancy\" sequences over simple, effective moves, explicitly labeling multiple mistakes as \"fancy play syndrome.\" In mistakes #7, #16, #18, #40, and #47, they note being \"tempted by a fancy maneuver\" or going for \"complicated\" ideas when simple alternatives existed, with mistake #47 concluding \"I need to focus on simple, short calculations, and avoid fancy play syndrome.\"","mistakeCount":5},{"title":"Psychological Aversion to Queen Trades","description":"The player demonstrates an irrational tendency to avoid queen exchanges even when beneficial for their position. In mistakes #13, #33, and #41, they explicitly note this psychological block, with mistake #33 stating \"I also psychologically was probably avoiding the queen exchange for no reason (Qe3 was perfectly safe here)\" and mistake #13 noting \"I have a blindness for both exchanging queens.\"","mistakeCount":3}]',50,1762813541419,'["cmhtpni1z000fs0tmjh9xfwo4","cmhtpk3tu000cs0tm1d85hkz9","cmhtpiqsu000as0tmrrph1qz9","cmhtph2uf0007s0tmknxtf21q","cmhtpg4tx0005s0tme5x3knjn","cmhtpebaa0002s0tmfzw7c1xi","cmhtkcu0900022ggek89uta5c","cmhsi7iwc00022glb5gxjeiov","cmhr0h1j300022gxi4zyogg2e","cmhqqszkc000f2gac8rumvhqt","cmhqqrxqo000d2gacnduiytyz","cmhqqr30y000b2gac57qzwa6b","cmhqpupdb00082gac2e9ekfp4","cmhqpau4c00052gaclu22i8hp","cmhqouy1c00022gacytoj2tbo","cmhqoeg0x00022g6kk76prlmz","cmhqm3hv900042ggzc056ax1s","cmhoar9ez00022g3ggzs1gr2b","cmhnvo229001m2ghesmyody1d","cmhnvl5ri001j2ghe48oqludj","cmhnvghg7001g2ghesi4ueewr","cmhnverm6001d2ghe5ski16eo","cmhnv9qsg001a2gheytde3n4d","cmhnv6jhz00172ghenzl80y36","cmhnv3rv300142ghe3vfyhh3i","cmhnv1k5g00112ghenz5j0ciw","cmhnv068n000y2ghel8qusd19","cmhnuv0ru000v2gheu1xibaqa","cmhnuou9q000s2ghe8ohfea18","cmhnulz55000p2ghe6mqsjftt","cmhnuk2up000m2ghe69dqz959","cmhnue655000j2ghed931hyfj","cmhnuaxuy000g2gheqb6lb0f7","cmhnu84yj000d2gheojxnf43y","cmhnu5wvm000a2ghe21rokhpz","cmhnu34ho00072ghe2i12xojn","cmhnu1uxe00052ghekihzscis","cmhntztdw00022gheeldf1xwq","cmhnrc34a00052g016f2b5fhx","cmhnqmbxf00022g01x6bubskj","cmhmnpwkg000l2gv7lclohiec","cmhmnoa2z000j2gv78mty3n4h","cmhmnlwk5000g2gv7cqcsvzxa","cm