INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmhwhkvh5000js0tglu51pew9','[{"title":"Psychological Blindness to Bishop-for-Knight Exchanges","description":"The player repeatedly acknowledges being \"blinded by clinging to the bishop pair\" (mistake #7) and has \"a bias toward worrying too much about bishop-for-knight exchanges\" (mistake #19). In mistakes #7, #19, #24, and #30, they explicitly note missing opportunities because they avoid trading bishops for knights, calling it a \"blind spot\" that causes them to miss \"''antipositional''\" moves that are actually tactically strong.","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Tunnel Vision and Automatic Move Syndrome","description":"The player frequently makes moves without proper consideration, noting \"automatic reaction\" (mistake #17), \"automatic recapture\" (mistakes #20, #28, #47), and \"tunnel vision\" (mistakes #1, #21, #46, #48). They explicitly state needing to \"avoid making assumptions and just calculate\" rather than playing moves reflexively, particularly with recaptures.","mistakeCount":9},{"title":"Psychological Aversion to King-Side Pawn Advances","description":"The player has identified \"a psychological bias against g7-g5 or g2-g4 in general when my King is castled\" (mistake #9) and is \"biased against this because it ''weakens'' my king\" (mistake #2). In mistakes #2 and #9, they explicitly recognize this prevents them from seeing the best attacking plans, noting they \"need to eliminate that\" mental block.","mistakeCount":2},{"title":"Missing Basic Captures and Candidate Moves","description":"The player repeatedly doesn''t consider simple captures before looking at complex ideas, noting \"I need to consider basic captures\" (mistake #8), \"didn''t even consider\" or \"didn''t even notice\" key moves (mistakes #17, #21, #22, #23, #26, #31, #40, #42, #48). They acknowledge needing to be \"open to all captures\" (mistake #1) as a fundamental checklist item that''s missing from their thought process.","mistakeCount":11},{"title":"Defense Psychology: Panic vs Centralization","description":"When defending with extra material, the player has a pattern of panicking instead of centralizing: \"I panicked and ran\" instead of playing \"Rxe5\" (mistake #10), \"I panicked a bit with Ne2, decentralizing\" instead of \"Qxd5\" (mistake #12). They explicitly note the principle: \"When up material and being attacked, if you''re panicking, just centralize\" but struggle to apply it in practice.","mistakeCount":2},{"title":"Fancy Play Syndrome Over Simple Solutions","description":"The player has recurring issues with \"fancy play syndrome\" (mistakes #8, #18, #27, #29) where they attempt complex maneuvers instead of simple, effective moves. They note playing \"a weird maneuver that looked fancy\" (mistake #8) and \"started some weird intermediate sequence\" (mistake #29) when straightforward moves were superior, explicitly recognizing the need to choose simple solutions \"unless there is a really good reason not to.\"","mistakeCount":4}]',50,1762981354841,'["cmhwhicw5000is0tgjb6qsi59","cmhwhfsdg000gs0tg684gmd4u","cmhwhan8q000es0tgedrv0nud","cmhwh85j2000bs0tgyyseevx3","cmhwh4gg30008s0tg41k9hv8c","cmhwh2u140006s0tgl9a0xdv2","cmhwh0cc90004s0tgbrzewqt6","cmhwgxtsw0002s0tgxq2pq8k8","cmhuxh2cf00082ge7wbdxcmmu","cmhuxerqj00052ge7maj5xnoy","cmhuxczwp00022ge7j6h0uck7","cmhtpni1z000fs0tmjh9xfwo4","cmhtpk3tu000cs0tm1d85hkz9","cmhtpiqsu000as0tmrrph1qz9","cmhtph2uf0007s0tmknxtf21q","cmhtpg4tx0005s0tme5x3knjn","cmhtpebaa0002s0tmfzw7c1xi","cmhtkcu0900022ggek89uta5c","cmhsi7iwc00022glb5gxjeiov","cmhr0h1j300022gxi4zyogg2e","cmhqqszkc000f2gac8rumvhqt","cmhqqrxqo000d2gacnduiytyz","cmhqqr30y000b2gac57qzwa6b","cmhqpupdb00082gac2e9ekfp4","cmhqpau4c00052gaclu22i8hp","cmhqouy1c00022gacytoj2tbo","cmhqoeg0x00022g6kk76prlmz","cmhqm3hv900042ggzc056ax1s","cmhoar9ez00022g3ggzs1gr2b","cmhnvo229001m2ghesmyody1d","cmhnvl5ri001j2ghe48oqludj","cmhnvghg7001g2ghesi4ueewr","cmhnverm6001d2ghe5ski16eo","cmhnv9qsg001a2gheytde3n4d","cmhnv6jhz001