INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmhz6upfr000k2gc706vfs0zk','[{"title":"Systematic Blind Spot: Sneaky Pins and Loose Pieces","description":"The player repeatedly misses tactical patterns involving pins, particularly \"sneaky pins\" where queens pin unprotected pieces against rooks (mistakes #3, #39, #45). In mistake #3, they note this is \"a common pattern blind spot for me,\" and in mistake #45 they recognize \"Total blindness, maybe a little psychological since the rook is opposite the queen.\" They also miss loose pieces creating tactical vulnerabilities (mistake #46).","mistakeCount":5},{"title":"Bishop-for-Knight Exchange Phobia Creating Multiple Mistakes","description":"The player has an explicitly acknowledged \"bishop-takes-knight bias\" and \"blindness for...exchanging bishop for knight\" that causes repeated errors. In mistake #1, they note the bias \"operating in reverse for my opponent,\" in mistake #14 they''re \"blinded by clinging to the bishop pair,\" and in mistake #26 they identify \"a bias toward worrying too much about bishop-for-knight exchanges.\" This fear causes them to miss strong tactical shots (mistakes #31, #37) and play awkward moves to avoid trades.","mistakeCount":7},{"title":"Defensive Panic Leading to Decentralization When Winning","description":"When up material but under attack, the player repeatedly \"panics\" and plays passive moves instead of centralizing pieces. In mistake #19, they note \"I panicked a bit with Ne2, decentralizing\" and discover \"When up material and being attacked, if you''re panicking, just centralize.\" Similar panic appears in mistakes #4, #17, and #27 where fear overrides calculating concrete defensive resources.","mistakeCount":6},{"title":"Tunnel Vision on Initial Plan Blocking Simple Captures","description":"The player frequently locks onto one idea and fails to consider simple captures or alternatives. In mistake #8, \"Tunnel vision: I wanted to take on a3 so I did\" missing a better tactical shot. In mistake #28, they miss \"clearly a better\" option due to \"Tunnel vision,\" and in mistake #40 they get \"too focused on recapturing the piece to notice the obvious\" winning move. They also make \"automatic\" moves without assessment (mistakes #24, #27, #35).","mistakeCount":8},{"title":"Psychological Blind Spot: g7-g5/g2-g4 Pawn Attacks Near Own King","description":"The player has identified a specific \"psychological bias against g7-g5 or g2-g4 in general when my King is castled\" that they \"need to eliminate.\" In mistakes #9 and #16, they repeatedly fail to consider this key attacking lever because they view it as weakening their king, even when attacking makes this irrelevant. They explicitly note being \"biased against this because it ''weakens'' my king but when you are attacking it doesn''t matter necessarily.\"","mistakeCount":3}]',50,1763144736328,'["cmhz6tm7f000j2gc72itfvfla","cmhz6s3vl000h2gc7m7kfauhp","cmhz6qhdo000e2gc79cbto7of","cmhz6o3u3000b2gc75nnji2pa","cmhz6io4800082gc791zcdhp1","cmhz6et2900052gc79x8wg6qf","cmhz65yvh00022gc74lc40jyl","cmhwhicw5000is0tgjb6qsi59","cmhwhfsdg000gs0tg684gmd4u","cmhwhan8q000es0tgedrv0nud","cmhwh85j2000bs0tgyyseevx3","cmhwh4gg30008s0tg41k9hv8c","cmhwh2u140006s0tgl9a0xdv2","cmhwh0cc90004s0tgbrzewqt6","cmhwgxtsw0002s0tgxq2pq8k8","cmhuxh2cf00082ge7wbdxcmmu","cmhuxerqj00052ge7maj5xnoy","cmhuxczwp00022ge7j6h0uck7","cmhtpni1z000fs0tmjh9xfwo4","cmhtpk3tu000cs0tm1d85hkz9","cmhtpiqsu000as0tmrrph1qz9","cmhtph2uf0007s0tmknxtf21q","cmhtpg4tx0005s0tme5x3knjn","cmhtpebaa0002s0tmfzw7c1xi","cmhtkcu0900022ggek89uta5c","cmhsi7iwc00022glb5gxjeiov","cmhr0h1j300022gxi4zyogg2e","cmhqqszkc000f2gac8rumvhqt","cmhqqrxqo000d2gacnduiytyz","cmhqqr30y000b2gac57qzwa6b","cmhqpupdb00082gac2e9ekfp4","cmhqpau4c00052gaclu22i8hp","cmhqouy1c00022gacytoj2tbo","cmhqoeg0x00022g6kk76prlmz","cmhqm3hv900042ggzc056ax1s","cmhoar9ez00022g3ggzs1gr2b","cmhnvo229001m2ghesmyody1d","cmhnvl5ri001j2ghe48oqludj","cmhnvghg7001g2ghesi4ueewr","cmhnverm6001d2ghe5ski16eo","cmhnv9qs