INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmi6hpjh000002g2fuu5oduew','[{"title":"Blind Spot: Missing ''Sneaky Pin'' Patterns","description":"The player has a recurring tactical blind spot with pins involving queens opposite rooks or pieces on loose squares. In mistakes #8, #44, #50, #66, they explicitly note missing \"sneaky pin\" patterns, often describing these as \"a common pattern blind spot\" where \"the rook is opposite the queen which usually plays to the rook''s advantage, but not if it is unprotected.\"","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Psychological Bias Against Bishop-for-Knight Trades","description":"The player repeatedly acknowledges avoiding beneficial bishop-for-knight exchanges due to an irrational attachment to the bishop pair. In mistakes #19, #31, #36, #42, they explicitly mention \"blinded by clinging to the bishop pair,\" having \"a bias toward worrying too much about bishop-for-knight exchanges,\" and noting that trading \"''antipositional'' bishop for knight\" is a \"blind spot.\"","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Fancy Play Syndrome Over Simple Solutions","description":"The player consistently overlooks simple, forcing moves in favor of complicated or \"fancy\" maneuvers. In mistakes #20, #30, #39, #41, #63, #70, they explicitly label this as \"fancy play syndrome,\" noting they miss \"very simple\" captures or moves because they''re \"tempted by a fancy maneuver\" or go \"for a complicated queen sacrifice\" instead of \"simple, short calculations.\"","mistakeCount":6},{"title":"Automatic Moves and Recaptures Without Calculation","description":"The player frequently makes moves reflexively without assessing tactical consequences, especially recaptures. In mistakes #29, #32, #40, #59, they describe making \"automatic reaction,\" \"automatic recapture,\" and moves \"without assessing\" or calculating, leading to missed tactics and hanging pieces.","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Psychological Aversion to Queen Trades and g-pawn Advances","description":"The player has iden