INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmi9ghm6q000k2gb9gtxlkzn8','[{"title":"Systematic Blindness to ''Sneaky Pins''","description":"The player has a recurring and self-identified blind spot for pins, particularly when ''the rook is opposite the queen'' or involving queens opposite rooks. In mistakes #21, #57, #63, #79, they explicitly note missing ''sneaky pins'' and describe this as a ''common pattern blind spot.'' The pattern is so consistent they use the specific phrase ''sneaky pin'' multiple times.","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Psychological Aversion to Bishop-Takes-Knight Exchanges","description":"The player repeatedly identifies a bias against exchanging bishops for knights, sometimes missing strong tactical opportunities. In mistakes #12, #19, #32, #44, #49, #55, they explicitly note being ''blinded by clinging to the bishop pair'' (mistake #32), having ''bishop-takes-knight blindness'' (mistake #12), and a ''bias toward worrying too much about bishop-for-knight exchanges'' (mistake #44). This psychological block even operates in reverse when judging opponent moves (mistake #19).","mistakeCount":6},{"title":"Missing g-pawn Breaks Due to King Safety Bias","description":"The player has identified a ''psychological bias against g7-g5 or g2-g4 in general when my King is castled'' (mistake #34), repeatedly missing critical attacking moves. In mistakes #8, #27, #34, they explicitly note this pattern, stating ''I''m biased against this because it ''weakens'' my king but when you are attacking it doesn''t matter necessarily'' (mistake #27). They recognize missing both g2-g4 and g7-g5 pawn breaks across multiple games.","mistakeCount":3},{"title":"Automatic Moves and Recaptures Without Calculation","description":"The player frequently makes ''automatic'' moves, particularly recaptures, without assessing tactical consequences. In mistakes #42, #45, #53, #72, #79, they explicitly use the word ''automatic'' and note not calculating at all. In mistake #72, they describe making ''an automatic recapture'' and note the need to ''avoid automatic moves,'' while in mistake #79 they admit ''I just didn''t actually calculate at all.''","mistakeCount":5},{"title":"Fancy Play Syndrome Leading to Missed Simple Wins","description":"The player repeatedly chooses complicated or ''fancy'' moves over simple, winning alternatives. In mistakes #2, #33, #43, #52, #54, #76, #83, they explicitly identify this pattern, noting instances where they ''went for unnecessary complications'' (mistake #2), missed ''the very simple'' winning move for something ''weird'' or ''fancy'' (mistakes #33, #54), or ''went for a complicated queen sacrifice'' instead of a simple trade (mistake #83). This connects to their stated need to ''consider basic captures before resorting to fanciness'' (mistake #33).","mistakeCount":7}]',87,1763765583506,'["cmi9g3xje000j2gb9t23bgq17","cmi9g3078000h2gb9yaapkcw1","cmi9fnyhw000e2gb9xute6k6e","cmi9f9o51000b2gb9twg1xrd6","cmi9f69iz00092gb9c3oj2yg4","cmi9f4qm000072gb95oaohll3","cmi9f41gq00052gb9f0u316ne","cmi9eml6g00022gb9n75kp9lz","cmi81ji5l000ekrydm8wytvjr","cmi818sq5000bkrydk07f5gfa","cmi8144bz0008kryd0de9zx7f","cmi80i5p00005krydyzq94l7k","cmi7zwug70002krydsmjbsno8","cmi6hiqub000c2gwtfvzqjha7","cmi6hhki3000a2gwtry7paoxg","cmi6hg78e00082gwtbnsvh4ev","cmi6gpkcj00052gwtel5ng5sb","cmi6fwii100022gwtsaubbtvc","cmhz6tm7f000j2gc72itfvfla","cmhz6s3vl000h2gc7m7kfauhp","cmhz6qhdo000e2gc79cbto7of","cmhz6o3u3000b2gc75nnji2pa","cmhz6io4800082gc791zcdhp1","cmhz6et2900052gc79x8wg6qf","cmhz65yvh00022gc74lc40jyl","cmhwhicw5000is0tgjb6qsi59","cmhwhfsdg000gs0tg684gmd4u","cmhwhan8q000es0tgedrv0nud","cmhwh85j2000bs0tgyyseevx3","cmhwh4gg30008s0tg41k9hv8c","cmhwh2u140006s0tgl9a0xdv2","cmhwh0cc90004s0tgbrzewqt6","cmhwgxtsw0002s0tgxq2pq8k8","cmhuxh2cf00082ge7wbdxcmmu","cmhuxerqj00052ge7maj5xnoy","cmhuxczwp00022ge7j6h0uck7","cmhtpni1z000fs0tmjh9xfwo4","cmhtpk3tu000cs0tm1d85hkz9","cmhtpiqsu000as0tmrrph1qz9","cmhtph2uf0007s0tmknxtf21q","cmhtpg4tx0005s0tme5x3knjn","cmhtpeba