INSERT INTO Insight VALUES('cmif2v367000g2gl0zozvl6ro','[{"title":"Bishop-Takes-Knight Blindness and Exchange Reluctance","description":"The player repeatedly acknowledges a bias against bishop-for-knight exchanges, both making and allowing them. In mistakes #4, #18, #25, #38, #50, #55, #61, they explicitly mention this pattern: \"running weakness with avoiding bishop-for-knight exchanges\" (#4), \"Another bishop takes knight blindness\" (#18), \"my ''bishop-takes-knight'' bias operating in reverse for my opponent\" (#25), \"I''m still blinded by clinging to the bishop pair\" (#38), and \"bias toward worrying too much about bishop-for-knight exchanges\" (#50).","mistakeCount":8},{"title":"Sneaky Pin Pattern Blindness (Queen-Rook Pins)","description":"The player has a recurring inability to see pins, especially \"sneaky pins\" involving queens opposite rooks. In mistakes #27, #63, #69, #85, they explicitly identify this: \"I did not even notice that Qxe8 was a threat because of the pin\" (#27), \"Again it was a queen opposite a rook sneaky pin that I overlooked\" (#63), \"maybe a little psychological since the rook is opposite the queen\" (#69). They recognize this as a \"common pattern blind spot\" (#27).","mistakeCount":4},{"title":"Psychological Bias Against g-file Pawn Advances","description":"The player identifies a specific psychological block about playing g2-g4 or g7-g5 when their king is castled on that side. In mistakes #14, #33, #40, they state: \"Similar bias toward missing g2-g4 or g7-g5, except when my King is castled on the queenside\" (#14), \"I''m biased against this because it ''weakens'' my king but when you are attacking it doesn''t matter\" (#33), and \"I have a psychological bias against g7-g5 or g2-g4 in general when my King is castled—need to eliminate that\" (#40).","mistakeCount":3},{"title":"Panic-Induced Sequential Blunders and Poor Defense","description":"The player explicitly mentions panicking multiple times, leading to compound errors or poor defensive choices. In mistakes #3, #13, #28, #41, #43, #82, they describe: \"panicked, and then committed a second blunder in a row\" (#3), \"I saw the threat...But simply h6 into g5 solves all my problems\" after panic (#13), \"Panicked in the endgame\" (#28), \"I panicked and ran with my king\" (#41), \"I panicked a bit with Ne2, decentralizing\" (#43), and \"panicked and played something extreme\" (#82).","mistakeCount":6},{"title":"Fancy Play Syndrome Over Simple Solutions","description":"The player repeatedly catches themselves choosing complicated, fancy moves over simple, strong alternatives. In mistakes #8, #39, #49, #58, #60, #82, #89, they explicitly label this as \"fancy play syndrome\" and note: \"I could just play Be5 here and cement my advantage. Instead I played Bg6\" (#8), \"the very simple axb6 axb6 Bd6 wins material. I need to consider basic captures before resorting to fanciness\" (#39), \"Could have just played the simple Ng4...Instead, started some weird intermediate sequence\" (#60), and \"I need to focus on simple, short calculations, and avoid fancy play syndrome\" (#89).","mistakeCount":7}]',93,1764105494480,'["cmif2t7fs000f2gl0yhmmt4et","cmif2c2o1000c2gl0vdlnw725","cmif27f5800092gl0hs8w4mgw","cmif26foy00072gl04rm8ip8q","cmif2342900042gl0vzxqgkcd","cmif21xp900022gl0rq7jzj4x","cmi9g3xje000j2gb9t23bgq17","cmi9g3078000h2gb9yaapkcw1","cmi9fnyhw000e2gb9xute6k6e","cmi9f9o51000b2gb9twg1xrd6","cmi9f69iz00092gb9c3oj2yg4","cmi9f4qm000072gb95oaohll3","cmi9f41gq00052gb9f0u316ne","cmi9eml6g00022gb9n75kp9lz","cmi81ji5l000ekrydm8wytvjr","cmi818sq5000bkrydk07f5gfa","cmi8144bz0008kryd0de9zx7f","cmi80i5p00005krydyzq94l7k","cmi7zwug70002krydsmjbsno8","cmi6hiqub000c2gwtfvzqjha7","cmi6hhki3000a2gwtry7paoxg","cmi6hg78e00082gwtbnsvh4ev","cmi6gpkcj00052gwtel5ng5sb","cmi6fwii100022gwtsaubbtvc","cmhz6tm7f000j2gc72itfvfla","cmhz6s3vl000h2gc7m7kfauhp","cmhz6qhdo000e2gc79cbto7of","cmhz6o3u3000b2gc75nnji2pa","cmhz6io4800082gc791zcdhp1","cmhz6et2900052gc79x8wg6qf"